WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.951
Developmental Biology

00:00:01.951 --> 00:00:04.622
Tooth Development (Odontogenesis):

00:00:04.622 --> 00:00:09.340
Initiation**: The dental lamina forms, signaling the start of tooth development.

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:13.665
Bud Stage**: Tooth buds emerge from the dental lamina and begin to take shape.

00:00:13.665 --> 00:00:20.778
Cap Stage**: The tooth bud transforms into the enamel organ, which will produce enamel through interactions with surrounding tissues.

00:00:20.778 --> 00:00:29.087
Bell Stage**: Cell specialization occurs within the enamel organ, producing ameloblasts for enamel and odontoblasts for dentin formation.

00:00:29.087 --> 00:00:35.898
Maturation**: The tissues undergo mineralization, hardening the enamel and dentin in preparation for tooth eruption.

00:00:35.898 --> 00:00:37.751
Embryonic Stages:

00:00:37.751 --> 00:00:44.717
Preimplantation**: From fertilization to the first week, the zygote develops into a blastocyst for implantation.

00:00:44.717 --> 00:00:48.561
Embryonic Period**: Weeks 2 to 8 are crucial for the formation of major

00:00:48.561 --> 00:00:54.703
organs, including facial and oral structures; any disruptions can lead to congenital abnormalities.

00:00:54.703 --> 00:01:02.157
Fetal Period**: From week 9 to birth, the fetus undergoes growth and maturation, refining the structures developed earlier.

00:01:02.157 --> 00:01:03.935
Oral Embryology:

00:01:03.935 --> 00:01:08.595
Formation of Layers**: The ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm are established

00:01:08.595 --> 00:01:12.072
during early embryogenesis, forming the basis for all tissues and

00:01:12.072 --> 00:01:12.932
organs.

00:01:12.932 --> 00:01:17.948
Facial Structure Development**: This phase involves creating facial bones, muscles, and

00:01:17.948 --> 00:01:22.153
oral structures, which are essential for functions like chewing and speaking.

00:01:22.153 --> 00:01:27.783
Proper development during this time is vital for functional and aesthetic outcomes in the oral and facial regions.
